Opportunity for Income Predictor, place-level

Author

JP Walsh

Published

January 23, 2024

Program for the creation of the Opportunity for Income Predictor at the place level

ACS Code: Initially written by Tina Chelidze and updated by JP Walsh 2022-2023.

Primary data derived from the IPUMS API.

Based on processes developed by Paul Johnson and Kevin Werner in SAS.

Housekeeping

Read in packages for use. If you do not have an IPUMS API key you will need to make one via the IPUMS website.

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(Hmisc)
library(ipumsr)
library(reactable)
library(srvyr)

options(scipen = 999)

#set_ipums_api_key("Your KEY", save = TRUE)

source(here::here("functions", "API", "extract_ipums.R"))
source(here::here("functions", "Calculations", "place_survey_quantiles.R"))

Read Data

Read in the ACS extracts using the extract_ipums function. Make sure to change the survey list to reflect what years you want to include in the data. Currently we are including three years of 1-year data (2018a, 2021a and 2022a) and two years of 5-year data (2018c and 2021c). 5-year 2022 data will be added pending its release.

Code 
acs <- extract_ipums(
  extract_name = "umf_data_18_22",
  extract_description = "Microdata pull for Mobility Metric Predictors. American Community Survey, years 2018, 2019 and 2022 (1 and 5-year).",
  survey = list("us2018a", "us2021a", "us2022a", "us2018c", "us2021c")
)

Look at the distribution of samples in the data.

Code 
acs %>% 
  count(sample) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = sample, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Samples, All Records") +
 geom_text(mapping = aes(label = n), vjust = -1) +    
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.1))) +
  labs(x = "ACS Samples",
       y = NULL)

Read in the PUMA to place crosswalk file. This file is created by the program generate_puma_place_crosswalks.rmd in the geographic-crosswalks folder.

Code 
puma_place_crosswalk <- read_csv(here::here("geographic-crosswalks", "data", "crosswalk_puma_to_place.csv"))

Crate a version of the crosswalk with just the place-level values of data quality variables for each crosswalk period.

Code 
place_puma <- puma_place_crosswalk %>%
  group_by(crosswalk_period, statefip, place) %>% 
  summarise(geographic_allocation_quality = mean(geographic_allocation_quality)) %>% 
  ungroup()

Clean Data

Missing data is reported in a variety of ways by IPUMS - listed below:

HHINCOME is missing it is reported as â9999999â. Vacancy is reported as â0â.

There is a large share of records missing HHINCOME. However, note there are no vacancy results by default of the structure of census data read in.

Code 
acs %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = hhincome)) +
  geom_density(color = "blue", fill = alpha("blue", 0.3)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Household Income Variable Results") +
  ylab("Density")

Code 
acs %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = vacancy)) +
  geom_density(color = "blue", fill = alpha("blue", 0.3)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Vacancy Variable Results") +
  ylab("Density")

Turn the missing/ânot in universeâ values for the hhincome variable into NAs.

Code 
acs_clean <- acs %>%
  mutate(hhincome = ifelse(hhincome == 9999999, NA_integer_,
                          hhincome)
  )

Look at distribution of HHINCOME after adjustment. Some outliers will still exist but bunching around the missing value should not be present.

Create race variable

Evaluate the values in the RACE and HISPAN variables.

  • IPUMS documented values for RACE:
    • 1 White
    • 2 Black/African American/Negro
    • 3 American Indian or Alaska Native
    • 4 Chinese
    • 5 Japanese
    • 6 Other Asian or Pacific Islander
    • 7 Other race
    • 8 Two major races
    • 9 Three or more major races
  • IPUMS documented values for HISPAN:
    • 0 Not Hispanic
    • 1 Mexican
    • 2 Puerto Rican
    • 3 Cuban
    • 4 Other
    • 9 Not Reported

The data show no cases of non-reporting for Hispan.

Code 
acs_clean %>% 
  count(race) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = race, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Race, All Records") +
 geom_text(mapping = aes(label = n), vjust = -1) +    
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.1))) +
  labs(x = "Race",
       y = NULL)

Code 
acs_clean %>%

  ggtitle("Hispan, All Records") +
 geom_text(mapping = aes(label = n), vjust = -1) +    
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.1))) +
  labs(x = "Hispan",
       y = NULL)

Create the race/ethnicity variable. For other race/ethnicity categories not coded as Hispanic, Hispan must be equal to âNot Hispanicâ.

Rename the values from number category to race label: +Race is 2 and Hispan is 0 = âBlack, Non-Hispanicâ +Hispan is >=1 and <=4 = âHispanicâ +Race is >=3 and <=9 and Hispan is 0 = âOther Races and Ethnicitiesâ +Race is 4 and Hispan is 0 = âWhite, Non-Hispanicâ

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>%
  mutate(subgroup = case_when((hispan == "Not Hispanic" & race == "White") ~ "White, Non-Hispanic",
                              (hispan == "Not Hispanic" & race == "Black/African American") ~ "Black, Non-Hispanic",
                              (hispan == "Not Hispanic" & !race %in% c("Black/African American", "White")) ~ "Other Races and Ethnicities",
                               hispan != "Not Hispanic" ~ "Hispanic"
  ))

Look at subgroup distribution.

Code

acs_clean <- acs_clean %>% 
  filter(!is.na(afact))

Also filter out cases where AFACT is equal to zero.

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>% 
  filter(afact > 0)

Adjust weight to account for PUMA-to-county mapping (those where unique_types do not equal 1).Drop PUMA flag variable from PUMA_place.

Apply the Adjust variable to household income. Adjust converts the dollar amounts to the amount that they would have been had they been earned entirely during the calendar year. This is to deal with households being surveyed at different times during the year.

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>%
  mutate(hhwt = hhwt*afact, 
         hhincome = hhincome*adjust
  )

Isolate data to include each household only once (PERNUM == 1 counts head of household only).

Code 
acs_clean <- acs_clean %>%
  filter(pernum == 1)

acs_clean <- acs_clean %>%

Create Income Metric

Create the income metric for each place overall and for race subgroups.

Objective: Calculate the 20th, 50th and 80th percentile of household income for all unique state+place combinations in all years.

Aggregation should be weighted by HHWT (this is a household level statistic).

All

Calculate income quantiles by place (1-year data).

Code 
metrics_income_all <- acs_clean %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "1year") %>%
  group_by(year, crosswalk_period, statefip, place) %>%
  summarise(
    pctl_income_20 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.2, na.rm = TRUE),
    pctl_income_50 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.5, na.rm = TRUE),
    pctl_income_80 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.8, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

Sort by year, state and place.

Code 
metrics_income_all <- metrics_income_all %>%
  arrange(year, statefip, place)

Create an indicator for data quality and suppression

Calculate the effective sample count for each county.

Code 
effective_sample <- acs_clean %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "1year") %>% 
  group_by(year, crosswalk_period, statefip, place) %>%
  summarise(effective_sample = sum(afact)) %>% 
  ungroup()

Merge the data quality flag on geographic allocation from the crosswalk on to the metric data.

Code 
metrics_income_all <- left_join(metrics_income_all, place_puma, by=c("crosswalk_period", "statefip","place"))

metrics_income_all <- left_join(metrics_income_all, effective_sample, by=c("year", "crosswalk_period", "statefip","place"))

Tabulate effective sample counts for each place, defined as the sum of the afact for all records in that place. Look at the distribution of places by potential cutoffs (30, 100, 300). This is to measure data quality for each place based on the number of records reported. In the 1-year data for all there are no cases of a place with less than 100 observations for 2018, 2021 and 2022.

Code 
metrics_income_all %>%
  mutate(
    effective_sample_cutoffs = case_when(
      effective_sample < 30 ~ "Less than 30",
      effective_sample >= 30 &
        effective_sample <= 100 ~ "Over 30 but 100 or less",
      effective_sample > 100 &
        effective_sample <= 300 ~ "Over 100 but 300 or less",
      TRUE ~ "Greater than 300"
    ),
    effective_sample_cutoffs = factor(
      effective_sample_cutoffs,
      levels = c(
        "Less than 30",
        "Over 30 but 100 or less",
        "Over 100 but 300 or less",
        "Greater than 300"
      )
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(year, effective_sample_cutoffs) %>%
  count() %>%
  mutate(supression_share = n / 485) %>%
  reactable()

Generate the quality variable. Mark cases where the effective sample is less than 100, these will be assigned a data quality of 3.

Code 
metrics_income_all <- metrics_income_all %>% 
  mutate(effective_sample_flag = ifelse(effective_sample < 100, 1, 0),
         pctl_20_quality = case_when(effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==1 ~ 1,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==2 ~ 2,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==3 ~ 3,
                                     effective_sample_flag==1 ~ 3),
         pctl_50_quality = case_when(effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==1 ~ 1,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==2 ~ 2,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==3 ~ 3,
                                     effective_sample_flag==1 ~ 3),
         pctl_80_quality = case_when(effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==1 ~ 1,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==2 ~ 2,
                                     effective_sample_flag==0 & geographic_allocation_quality==3 ~ 3,
                                     effective_sample_flag==1 ~ 3)
  )

We do not want to show values that are calculated from less than 30 samples in the data. These points will be suppressed and shown as missing or NA. Suppress the results for values generated from less than 30 samples.

Code 
metrics_income_all <- metrics_income_all %>% 
  mutate_at(c("pctl_income_20", "pctl_income_50", "pctl_income_80"), ~if_else(effective_sample < 30, NA_integer_, .))

Keep only relevant variables.

Code 
metrics_income_all <- metrics_income_all %>% 
  select(year, statefip, place, pctl_income_20, pctl_20_quality, 
         pctl_income_50, pctl_50_quality, pctl_income_80, 
         pctl_80_quality)

Subgroups

Calculate income quantiles by race/ethnicity and place (5-year data).

Code 
metrics_income_subgroup <- acs_clean %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "5year") %>%
  group_by(year, crosswalk_period, statefip, place, subgroup) %>%
  summarise(
    pctl_income_20 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.2, na.rm = TRUE),
    pctl_income_50 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.5, na.rm = TRUE),
    pctl_income_80 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.8, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(subgroup_type = "race-ethnicity")

Calculate quantiles for all households with the 5-year data. To be appended onto the subgroup data by race/ethnicity.

Code 
metrics_income_subgroup_all <- acs_clean %>%
  filter(sample_structure == "5year") %>%
  group_by(year, crosswalk_period, statefip, place) %>%
  summarise(
    pctl_income_20 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.2, na.rm = TRUE),
    pctl_income_50 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.5, na.rm = TRUE),
    pctl_income_80 = Hmisc::wtd.quantile(hhincome, weights = hhwt, probs = 0.8, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(subgroup_type = "all",
         subgroup = "All")

  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Income percentiles (5-year data)") +
  ylab("Density")

Rename state.

Code 
metrics_income_all <- metrics_income_all %>% 
  rename("state" = "statefip")

metrics_income_sub <- metrics_income_sub %>% 
  rename("state" = "statefip")

Order the variables how we want.

Code 
metrics_income_all <- metrics_income_all %>% 
  select(year, state, place, pctl_income_20, pctl_20_quality, pctl_income_50, 
         pctl_50_quality, pctl_income_80, pctl_80_quality)

metrics_income_sub <- metrics_income_sub %>% 
  select(year, state, place, subgroup_type, subgroup, pctl_income_20, pctl_20_quality, pctl_income_50, 
         pctl_50_quality, pctl_income_80, pctl_80_quality)
